This question will resolve as Yes if, before January 1, 2025, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) is officially recognized as playing a pivotal role in responding to a global health crisis. A "pivotal role" is defined as the CDC leading or co-leading efforts in at least one of the following areas: 
- Disease surveillance and reporting; 
- Development or distribution of vaccines or treatments; 
- Implementation of public health measures and guidelines. 

Recognition must come from either an official statement by the World Health Organization (WHO), the United Nations (UN), or a consensus in reporting from at least three major news organizations (BBC, The Guardian, New York Times, Washington Post). 

In the event that multiple organizations are recognized, the CDC must be cited as a primary contributor. Temporary or advisory roles do not meet the criteria for a pivotal role.

