This question will resolve as Yes if, by December 31, 2030, a major discovery in the natural sciences (e.g., physics, biology, chemistry) is officially recognized to have significantly influenced the development of sports science, specifically in the context of tennis. The influence must be evident in at least one of the following areas:
- Athletic performance enhancement through new training methods or equipment;
- Injury prevention or recovery;
- Game strategy optimization based on new scientific insights.
The discovery must be acknowledged by a reputable scientific body or journal and its application in tennis must be documented by credible sources such as the International Tennis Federation (ITF), major sports science journals, or reputable news outlets (BBC, The New York Times, ESPN). In the absence of direct acknowledgment by these entities, consensus among at least three experts in the field, reported by reputable news sources, will suffice. Temporary or experimental applications do not meet this criterion.

